{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48882"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy is brought to the General Practice clinic by his parents, who express concerns about his academic performance. The parents note that, compared to his peers, he seems to be struggling academically. While he achieved his previous developmental milestones, there are notable differences to his peers in the community, at home and at school. The child rarely engages with peers or teachers, and he often appears inattentive to classroom activities. Furthermore, he shows limited interest in participating in group projects. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. During the assessment, the child exhibits challenges in sustaining attention during academic tasks, and he occasionally displays repetitive hand movements, particularly when looking at the bright light in the office.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following symptoms is more suggestive of autism spectrum disorder than attention deficit hyperactivity disorder?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Struggling academically compared to peers","Limited interest in participation in group projects","Difficulty sustaining attention during academic tasks","Repetitive hand movements when looking at bright lights","Inattentiveness to classroom activities"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAutism spectrum disorder (ASD) is defined in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual, 5th Edition (DSM-5) as a neurodevelopmental disorder characterised by (1) persistent deficits in communication and social interaction across multiple contexts, and (2) restricted, repetitive patterns of behaviour, interests or activities. Both criteria need to be met for the diagnosis to be made. Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is defined by a persistent pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main symptom which is more suggestive of ASD over ADHD is the manifestation of \u003Cstrong\u003Erepetitive hand movements, particularly when looking at bright lights\u003C/strong\u003E. This behavior aligns with the restricted, repetitive patterns of behaviour characteristic of ASD, especially when linked to sensory stimuli. Such repetitive behaviors are not typically associated with ADHD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStruggling academically compared to peers\u003C/strong\u003E can be observed in both ASD and ADHD, as well as various other conditions, and is not specific to either disorder. Therefore, it is not a distinguishing feature between ASD and ADHD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimited interest in participation in group projects\u003C/strong\u003E could be indicative of social difficulties seen in ASD, but it could also be due to inattention or impulsivity in ADHD. As such, it is not a clear differentiator between the two conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifficulty sustaining attention during academic tasks\u003C/strong\u003E is a hallmark symptom of ADHD and is not specific to ASD. While individuals with ASD may have attention difficulties, this symptom alone does not distinguish ASD from ADHD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInattentiveness to classroom activities\u003C/strong\u003E is another symptom that can be present in both ASD and ADHD. In ASD, it might be due to preoccupation with specific interests, while in ADHD it\u0027s typically due to difficulty maintaining focus. Therefore, this symptom alone is not more suggestive of one disorder over the other.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly red flags for autism spectrum disorder include poor eye contact, no response to name, lack of showing (protodeclarative) and sharing, no gesturing by 12 months, and loss of language or social skills. If red flags are present, the child should be referred from primary care to specialists including a developmental paediatrician, and in some cases a paediatric neurologist and child psychiatrist for further assessment and diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autism spectrum disorder should always be considered where there are poor language and social skills, poor response to personal contact, and repetitive movements to sensory stimuli.","Repetitive behaviors, particularly in response to sensory stimuli, are more characteristic of autism spectrum disorder than attention deficit hyperactivity disorder."],"references":["Hodges H, Fealko C, Soares N. Autism spectrum disorder: definition, epidemiology, causes, and clinical evaluation. Transl Pediatr. 2020;9(Suppl 1):S55-S65.","Rommelse, N., Visser, J. \u0026 Hartman, C. Differentiating between ADHD and ASD in childhood: some directions for practitioners. Eur Child Adolesc Psychiatry 27, 679\u2013681 (2018). https://doi.org/10.1007/s00787-018-1165-5"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33880"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2069"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33880"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T11:39:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T20:37:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2069"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48882"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"